Purpose of this Document

The purpose of this document is to provide instructions on how to utilize packages for R that are available on GitHub, but are not currently easily accessible from repositories like CRAN.

Getting Started

To get started we are going to need to install a few packages from the CRAN (more on this later). Today we are going to use the githubinstall, install_github, remotes, and gapminder packages. The first three are for downloading and installing packages from GitHub. The final package will be used to download the gapminder dataset for use with the various packages we download from GitHub.

# Packages to install 
  # install.packages("tidyverse)
  # install.packages("githubinstall")
  # install.packages("install_github")
  # install.packages("remotes")
  # install.packages("gapminder")

# Loading up the tidyverse package
library(tidyverse)
gm <- gapminder::gapminder

Typical Package Implementation

In general, when trying to add functionality to base R, you search for a package on the CRAN (the Comprehensive R Archive Network) and simply use the install.packages function to download and install the package and functionality. Packages on the CRAN have gone through a vetting process to ensure that they are safe and do what they say they will do. However, oftentimes you find a function or package that you would like to use, but it has not gone through the CRAN vetting process and is only available on sites like GitHub. There are also times when a package is available on the CRAN, but certain functionality that you want to utilize has not been vetted or added to the CRAN. Developers will often have development or beta versions of their packages that they will make available via GitHub before they go on the CRAN.

Methods for Utilizing GitHub packages

Using the github_install, and install_github packages

github_install

github_install

install_github

The install_github has an extra requirement above github_install, in that you need to know the name of the repository/repo. This is both a positive and a negative. It is positive because it ensures that you are getting the right package and not doing a best guess, as github_install does. However, this does decrease the amount of flexibility you have when downloading and installing packages from github and adds an extra burden to the user.

For this example, we are going to use the ggtrace package. The ggtrace package allows for the highlighting of specific portions of a graph. This package is only available on github.

In order to use install_github you need to ensure that you have the devtools package installed and loaded.

library(devtools)

devtools::install_github("rnabioco/ggtrace")

gm %>% group_by(year, continent) %>% 
  summarize(lifeExp = mean(lifeExp)) %>% 
ggplot(aes(year, lifeExp, color = continent)) +
  theme_minimal() +
  ggtrace::geom_line_trace(
    trace_position    = year < 1962 & year > 1950,
    stroke            = 1,
    background_params = list(color = NA, fill = "grey75")
  )

gm %>% 
ggplot(aes(year, lifeExp, color = continent)) +
  theme_minimal() +
  ggtrace::geom_point_trace(
    trace_position    = (continent == "Americas" | country == "Afghanistan") & year == 1997,
    fill              = "orange",
    background_params = list(color = NA, fill = "blue")
  )

Manually Downloading Packages

Another possible way to get packages from GitHub (and also other sources) is to manually download a zipped file version of the package. This can be done using another version of the install_ family of functions from the devtools and remotes packages. Below, I have steps that you would take to find, download, and install a package to your local machine.

# Use .libPaths() to find your local directory
.libPaths()

# Save your local directory as dir
dir <- .libPaths()[1]

Clone GitHub page as Zip file

Download zip file and unzip the file in your local directory (the dir object)

Use the install_local function from devtools/remotes to install the package

# install_local("path/to/unzipped_pkg_zip_file")
install_local(paste0(dir, "/ggtech-master/ggtech-master"), force = TRUE)

# force = TRUE will overwrite an already installed version
